description:
# Problem
In `rust/lichen-link/src/schnorr.rs:170-185`, the `build_signable` function writes to a 256-byte buffer without bounds checking:

```rust
fn build_signable<'a>(
    buf: &'a mut [u8; 256],
    epoch: u8,
    seqnum: LinkSeqNum,
    dst_addr: &[u8],
    inner_payload: &[u8],
) -> &'a [u8] {
    buf[0] = epoch;
    buf[1..3].copy_from_slice(&seqnum.to_be_bytes());
    let mut off = 3;
    buf[off..off + dst_addr.len()].copy_from_slice(dst_addr);  // can panic
    off += dst_addr.len();
    buf[off..off + inner_payload.len()].copy_from_slice(inner_payload);  // can panic
    off += inner_payload.len();
    &buf[..off]
}
```

## What goes wrong
If `3 + dst_addr.len() + inner_payload.len() > 256`, this panics in debug or corrupts memory in release.

The comment says "max 202 bytes for LoRa" but:
1. This is not enforced at compile time or runtime
2. The function is `pub` (can be called from outside the module)
3. A contributor copying this pattern will assume the 256-byte buffer is always sufficient

## Trigger
Call `sign_frame` or `verify_frame` with `dst_addr.len() + inner_payload.len() > 253`.

## Fix
Return `Result<&'a [u8], SigningError>` and check bounds before copying.
